<span class="displaytext"><b>for immediate release</b><br/> <b>contact:</b> (candidate last) press shop (857) 288-6390 <p><b> <u>governor (candidate last)'s tax-free savings plan for florida families:</u> </b> </p><p><b>on friday, governor (candidate full) outlined his middle class tax savings plan.</b> governor (candidate last)'s plan will allow the middle class in florida to save tax-free by changing the tax rate on interest, capital gains and dividends to absolutely 0%. by helping more floridians save and invest, we can meet the challenges of an aging population and ensure the financial security of america. </p><p>- <b>governor (candidate last)'s plan will allow over 95% of american families to save and invest tax-free.</b> any taxpayer with adjusted gross income of under $200,000 would pay a tax rate of absolutely 0% on all of the income they earn from their savings, capital gains and dividends. </p><p><b>governor (candidate last)'s plan will help millions of floridians save and invest tax-free. for instance, according to 2005 tax returns:</b> </p><p><b>- 3,173,863 florida taxpayers who earned interest could have benefited from this tax break. <br/> - 1,651,574 florida taxpayers who earned dividends could have benefited from this tax break. <br/> - 1,437,597 florida taxpayers who earned capital gains could have benefited from this tax break. <br/></b> <br/> <b> <u>governor (candidate last)'s plan will help americans build wealth and become homeowners:</u> </b> </p><p><b>governor (candidate last)'s plan will help families save for new homes.</b> recent housing market difficulties offer an important reason for helping more people save and invest. as the market softens, credit has tightened. therefore lending standards will become much tougher. as exotic loans become less widespread, the traditional practice of saving for a home down-payment will be the new standard. governor (candidate last)'s plan will help floridians save for down-payments and achieve the american dream of home ownership. </p><p>- <b>governor (candidate last)'s plan will put more money in the hands of existing homeowners.</b> by providing taxpayers with a 0% tax rate on savings, the plan will help homeowners meet their current mortgage payments. this tax cut will put more money into the hands of florida homeowners. </p><p><b> <u>governor (candidate last)'s plan builds upon and extends pro-growth tax policies: <br/></u> </b> <br/> <b>governor (candidate last)'s plan builds on pro-growth tax policies initiated in 2003.</b> in 2003, the united states passed major cuts in the tax rate on capital gains and dividends, instituting a new, lower top rate of 15%. these tax cuts galvanized our economy. floridians were able to keep more of their capital gains and reinvest in the economy: </p><p><b>- the rate of growth in our economy more than tripled, going from 0.8% in the two years before the rate cuts to 3.1% in the two years following the tax cuts. </b></p><p>- following the capital gains tax rate cut in 2003, capital gains tax receipts actually increased from $58 billion in 2002 to $103 billion in 2006. <br/> <br/> <b> <u>governor (candidate last)'s pro-growth tax agenda:</u> </b> </p><p><b>governor (candidate last) has proposed a strong tax relief agenda to strengthen florida families.</b> governor (candidate last) will make the bush tax relief permanent, cut tax rates for all floridians, abolish the death tax, and make the corporate tax rate more competitive with the rest of the world. </p><p>- <a href="http://www.(candidate full).com/news/press-releases/abolishing_the_death_tax">click here</a> to read governor (candidate last)'s plan to cut taxes. </p><p><b>by making the bush tax relief permanent, governor (candidate last) will preserve tax relief for millions of floridians:</b> </p><p><b>- 6,751,000 total floridians benefited from the tax relief in 2006. <br/> - 5,937,000 floridians benefited from the rate reduction in the lowest tax bracket in 2006. <br/> - 1,933,000 floridians couples saw a reduction in the marriage penalty in 2006. <br/> - 1,692,000 floridians taxpayers benefited from the increased child credit in 2006.</b></p></span>



